Number of Regions in MSRAsubscriptùëÄSRAM_{\text{SRA}}.
In Tab.¬†4(a), we show results for different numbers of regions in MSRAsubscriptùëÄSRAM_{\text{SRA}}.
Thereby, without our attention MSRAsubscriptùëÄSRAM_{\text{SRA}} (number of regions = 0), the accuracy is deliberately good, which suggests the effectiveness and versatility of Patch-PnùëõnP.
Nevertheless, the overall accuracy can be further improved with increasing number of regions in MSRAsubscriptùëÄSRAM_{\text{SRA}}, despite starting to saturate around 64 regions.
Thus, we use 64 regions for MSRAsubscriptùëÄSRAM_{\text{SRA}} in all other experiments as trade-off between accuracy and memory.

As shown in Tab.¬†4(b), Patch-PnùëõnP is more accurate than traditional PnùëõnP/RANSAC (B0 \vsA0),
PointNet-like PnùëõnP (B0 \vsC0) and BPnùëõnP (B0 \vsC1) in estimating the 6D pose.
Furthermore, in terms of rotation, our Patch-PnùëõnP outperforms PointNet-like PnùëõnP by a large margin,
which proves the importance of exploiting the ordering within the correspondences.
Noteworthy, Patch-PnùëõnP is much faster in inference and up to 4√ó\times faster in training than BPnùëõnP, since the latter relies on PnùëõnP/RANSAC for both phases.

Parameterization of 6D Pose.
In Tab.¬†4(b), we illustrate the impact of our proposed 6D pose parameterization.
In particular, the 6-dimensional ùêë6dsubscriptùêë6d\mathbf{R}_{\text{6d}} (Eq.¬†1)
achieves a much more accurate estimate of ùêëùêë\mathbf{R} than commonly used representations such as
unit quaternions¬†[60, 27],
log quaternions¬†[37] and the Lie algebra-based vectors¬†[11] (c.f. B0 \vsD1-D3, and G0 \vsG2).
Moreover, we can deduce that the allocentric representation is significantly stronger than the egocentric formulation (B0 \vsD0).

Ablation on Pose Loss.
As mentioned in Section¬†3.1, the loss function has an impact on direct 6D pose regression.
In Tab.¬†4(b), we compare our disentangled ‚ÑíPosesubscript‚ÑíPose\mathcal{L}_{\text{Pose}} to a simple angular loss and
the Point-Matching loss¬†[27] (F0).
Furthermore, we present its disentangled versions following¬†[46].
As shown in (B0 and F0-F4), all variants of the PM loss are clearly better than the angular loss in terms of rotation estimation.
In addition, disentangling the rotation ùêëùêë\mathbf{R} and distance tzsubscriptùë°ùëßt_{z} in ‚ÑíPMsubscript‚ÑíPM\mathcal{L}_{\text{PM}} largely enhances the rotation accuracy.
Nonetheless, the overall performance is slightly inferior to our disentangled formulation ‚ÑíPosesubscript‚ÑíPose\mathcal{L}_{\text{Pose}}, which disentangles ùê≠SITEsubscriptùê≠SITE\mathbf{t}_{\text{SITE}} rather than the 3D translation ùê≠ùê≠\mathbf{t}.
It is worth noting that ‚Ñíùêë,symsubscript‚Ñíùêësym\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{R},\text{sym}} has a rather insignificant contribution compared with ‚Ñíùêësubscript‚Ñíùêë\mathcal{L}_{\mathbf{R}}.
This can be accounted to the lack of severe symmetries in LM and to our proposed surface region attention MSRAsubscriptùëÄSRAM_{\text{SRA}}.

Effectiveness of Geometry-Guided Direct Regression.
Furthermore, we train GDR-Net leveraging only our pose loss ‚ÑíPosesubscript‚ÑíPose\mathcal{L}_{\text{Pose}} by discarding the geometric supervision ‚ÑíGeomsubscript‚ÑíGeom\mathcal{L}_{\text{Geom}}.
Surprisingly, even the simple version outperforms CDPN¬†[28] \wrtADD(-S) 0.1d, when employing ùêë6dsubscriptùêë6d\mathbf{R}_{\text{6d}} for rotation (Tab.¬†4(b) G0 \vsA0).
Yet, we clearly outperform our baseline using GDR-Net with explicit geometric guidance.
If we predict the rotation as allocentric quaternions, the accuracy decreases (G2 \vsG0),
which can partially account for the weak performance of
previous direct methods¬†[60, 11].
Moreover, when we remove the guidance of M2DsubscriptùëÄ2DM_{\text{2D}}, the accuracy drops significantly (G0 \vsG1).
Based on these results, we can see that an appropriate geometric guidance is essential for direct 6D pose regression.

Direct pose regression
also enhances the learning of geometric features as the error signal from pose can be backpropagated.
Tab.¬†4(b) (B1, B2) shows that when evaluating GDR-Net with
PnùëõnP/RANSAC from the predicted M2D-3DsubscriptùëÄ2D-3DM_{\text{2D-3D}}, the overall performance exceeds CDPN¬†[28].
Similar to CDPN, we run tests using PnùëõnP/RANSAC for ùêëùêë\mathbf{R} and Patch-PnùëõnP for ùê≠ùê≠\mathbf{t},
which achieves the overall best accuracy (B2).
This demonstrates that our unified GDR-Net can leverage the best of both worlds, namely, geometry-based indirect methods and direct methods.

Effectiveness of Detection and Pose Decoupling.
Similar to CDPN¬†[28], we decouple the detector and GDR-Net by means of Dynamic Zoom-In (DZI).
When evaluating GDR-Net with the Yolov3 detections from¬†[28], the overall accuracy only drops slightly while the accuracy for ADD(-S) 0.1d almost remains unchanged (Tab.¬†4(b) H0).

Results on LM-O.
¬†Tab.¬†2¬†presents the results of GDR-Net compared with state-of-the-art methods on LM-O.
When trained with ‚Äúreal+syn‚Äù, our single GDR-Net is comparable to [47, 62].
Nevertheless, using one network per object, we easily surpass state of the art without refinement.
Moreover, our GDR-Net trained with ‚Äúreal+pbr‚Äù even outperforms the refinement-based method DeepIM¬†[27].

Results on YCB-V.
We compare GDR-Net to state-of-the-art approaches on YCB-V in Tab.¬†3 (see supplement for detailed results).
Our GDR-Net trained one network per object exceeds again state of the art, even without leveraging any refinement.
Our single model for all objects is also comparable to the refinement-based methods such as [27, 25] \wrtAUC of ADD-S metric. Noteworthy, our approach runs much faster than the methods requiring refinement.
